A person may appeal to the Supreme Court against any decision made by the Minister or Director to do all or any of the following:
* to require an EIA under section 17;
* to reject an application under section 23 or section 34;
* to impose terms and conditions on any approval given under section 23 or section 34;
* to issue a direction under section 26;
* to make a decision prescribed by the regulations as a decision in respect of which an appeal can be made.
* confirm, reverse or modify the decision appealed against, and make such orders and give such directions to the Minister, Director or Council as may be necessary to give effect to the Court's decision; or
* refer the matter back to the Minister, Director or Council with directions to reconsider the whole or any specified part of the matter.

The Minister may make regulations to give effect to the purposes and provisions of this Act, including for all or any of the following:
* to establish criteria for the licensing of environmental practitioners and environmental laboratories or analytical facilities;
* to prescribe and promote standards, guidelines or codes of environmental practice to give effect to any requirement under this Act;
* to establish alternate dispute resolution processes for resolving environmental disputes, including the prescribing of criteria for the appointment of qualified persons to act as a mediator, arbitrator or facilitator;
* to provide for the variation of any environmental assessment procedure;
* to prescribe fees and charges in respect of any application made or service provided under this Act - including for the purpose of expert review of applications;
* to control the taking or use of specified species;
* to provide for the registration of Community Conservation Areas;
* to establish conditions or model agreements for bioprospecting.
* regulating the environmental effects of:
	* the importation and transportation of hazardous substances;
	* the proposed introduction of foreign organisms;
	* pests and weeds;
	* waste management;
	* air and water pollution;
	* regulating the harvesting of marine resources;
	* providing for the containment, isolation, seizure, transportation, safe-keeping or disposal of any species of wild flora or fauna.
